        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We choose to use one high spectral resolution baseband centered on the sky frequency of the redshifted CO(2-1) line. We use no binning, so as to achieve the highest spectral resolution of 1.8 km/s needed to resolve any possible absorption against the radio AGN, and cover a total bandwidth of 3500 km/s, which assures that we also fully cover any possible outflow. 

The other three basebands are used for continuum in TDM mode, which will allow us to achieve an accurate estimate of the continuum in this band.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The maximum recoverable scale with our selected configuration is approximately 5 arcsec, which is much larger than the expected extent of our target (the r-band optical emission extends to about 1 arcsec). Therefore, we do not risk loosing an CO flux on large scales. A spatial resolution of 0.5 arcsec is well matched to the optical extent and will allow us to acertain whether the CO is centrally concentrated or offset with respect to the nucleus. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our goal is to detect CO(2-1) and determine its distribution in a young radio galaxy at z = 0.44. Assuming our target is a large gas-rich galaxy, with a total molecular gas mass of M_H2 = 5 x 10^9 M_solar and a conservative Milky Way H2/CO conversion factor of X_CO = 2 x 10^20 cm^-2/(K km/s), we predict an integrated flux density of S = 0.428 Jy km/s. Further assuming a typical line width of 100 km/s, we estimate a peak flux density of 4.28 mJy. In order to achieve a detection of CO greater than 5 sigma we therefore request an RMS sensitivity of 0.86 mJy per beam. Our chosen sensitivity bandwidth of 10 km/s enables sampling of 10 spectral bins across the line, allowing us to sufficiently resolve the spectral profile and bin the data if required.

Extrapolating the spectral behaviour of the radio source between 25 GHz and 97GHz, we predict a 160GHz continuum flux density of 100 mJy. The HI absorption (discovered using ASKAP) has several components ranging in width from 5 to 300 km/s. At the maximum resolution of 1.8 km/s available for our correlator set-up, we are able to sample the narrowest absorption component with an rms optical depth sensitivity of 2 per cent per channel, which is well matched to the CO optical depths seen in other similar systems.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
